I"9<p>Variables can be declared <strong>locally</strong> or <strong>globally</strong>. These two words basically defines the scope of a variable. It means the region upto which you can use any declared variable. In php, you can declare the variables both locally and globally. In order to use a global variable youâ€™ve to use the keyword <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">global</code>.</p>

<p>Here is a very basic example for the scope of variables,</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;?php
$name="anil";
function getName(){
    $name="peter";
    global $name;
    $name="peter";
    echo "local var: $name";
}


getName();
echo "&lt;br/&gt;";
echo $name;
?&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>Also, you can use the global variables within the nested functions. Keep in mind only the first one globally defined variable will be used within all nested functions. Take a look at it,</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;?php
$name="anil";
function test(){
    $name="peter";
    echo $name;

    function innerTest(){
        global $name;
        echo $name;
    }
}

test();
echo "&lt;br&gt;/";
innerTest();
echo "&lt;br&gt;/";
echo $name;;
?&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>
